00:15:59,710 --> 00:16:03,559
They manufacture and market over 300
different products around the world.

235
00:16:03,559 --> 00:16:10,600
P&G spent millions of dollars developing
Pur, a combined coagulant flocculant

236
00:16:10,600 --> 00:16:15,390
and disinfectant product in its corporate
social responsibility program, and then

237
00:16:15,390 --> 00:16:19,790
tried to establish it as a commercial
product with testing, test

238
00:16:19,790 --> 00:16:22,350
marketing for several years in Vietnam,

239
00:16:22,350 --> 00:16:25,245
Guatemala, the Philippines, Morocco, and
Pakistan.

240
00:16:25,245 --> 00:16:30,425
It cost P&G about $0.04 per sachet to
produce Pur which can treat ten liters of

241
00:16:30,425 --> 00:16:36,035
water, and they tried to sell the product
for 0.08 to $0.10 cents per sachet.

242
00:16:36,035 --> 00:16:41,630
P&G learned a lot from these experiments,
but after three years when sales

243
00:16:41,630 --> 00:16:44,140
did not meet targets, they concluded that

244
00:16:44,140 --> 00:16:46,879
the product wasn't likely to become
profitable.

245
00:16:49,476 --> 00:16:54,150
So P&G reconsidered its business plan for
Pur and

246
00:16:54,150 --> 00:16:57,710
in 2005, committed to a non-commercial
approach, where sachets would

247
00:16:57,710 --> 00:17:01,010
be sold at production cost, to programs
targeting people

248
00:17:01,010 --> 00:17:05,429
without safe drinking water, especially
children in low income countries.

249
00:17:06,490 --> 00:17:10,390
This proved to be a more successful
approach and within a few years, they

250
00:17:10,390 --> 00:17:13,440
had sold 57 million sachets compared to

251
00:17:13,440 --> 00:17:15,860
only 3 million during the commercial
trials.

252
00:17:17,810 --> 00:17:21,970
NGOs and social marketing groups like PSI
are key partners now.

253
00:17:23,040 --> 00:17:25,420
And in addition to distribution through
social marketing

254
00:17:25,420 --> 00:17:28,890
channels, Pur has been very popular for
emergency

255
00:17:28,890 --> 00:17:31,460
response, in part because it can treat
highly

256
00:17:31,460 --> 00:17:35,485
turbid waters which cause problems with
other products.

257
00:17:35,485 --> 00:17:40,710
P&G is also experimenting with sales to
campers in high income

258
00:17:40,710 --> 00:17:44,590
settings with the aim of cross subsidizing
the main BOP market.

259
00:17:45,820 --> 00:17:51,066
Pur has now been re-branded as the P&G
purifier of

260
00:17:51,066 --> 00:17:56,130
water and sits firmly in P&G's CSR
portfolio.

261
00:17:56,130 --> 00:17:58,290
Well, what about those charities or pure

262
00:17:58,290 --> 00:18:02,330
not for profit groups described in UNICEFs
framework.

263
00:18:02,330 --> 00:18:04,780
Well, there are not really many groups out
there today

264
00:18:04,780 --> 00:18:08,870
who don't care at all about cost recovery
from consumers.

265
00:18:08,870 --> 00:18:12,140
It's become conventional wisdom in large
part because of the

266
00:18:12,140 --> 00:18:16,690
successes of social marketing initiatives
that when people pay something

267
00:18:16,690 --> 00:18:19,720
for products, they become aware of the
value and in

268
00:18:19,720 --> 00:18:23,759
turn are more motivated to use and
maintain them carefully.

269
00:18:24,800 --> 00:18:27,450
So even purely charity driven
organizations

270
00:18:27,450 --> 00:18:29,680
today will often expect a nominal

271
00:18:29,680 --> 00:18:34,560
contribution from users either in cash or
in kind through labor and time.

272
00:18:34,560 --> 00:18:40,580
Two examples of not for profit HWTS
initiatives are SODIS

273
00:18:40,580 --> 00:18:45,790
and Biosand filters as promoted by the
NGO, Clear Cambodia.

274
00:18:45,790 --> 00:18:49,880
With SODIS, the cost of products the
plastic bottles, is very small.

275
00:18:49,880 --> 00:18:53,570
Though in some areas, purchasing plastic
bottles is a barrier to uptake.

276
00:18:54,970 --> 00:18:59,080
But the main costs of the program are
training and social mobilization

277
00:18:59,080 --> 00:19:01,480
typically through household visits, and
these

278
00:19:01,480 --> 00:19:04,340
costs are subsidized through donor
support.

279
00:19:04,340 --> 00:19:06,920
Similarly, Clear Cambodia is supported by
the

280
00:19:06,920 --> 00:19:10,970
charity, Samaritan's Purse, in its Biosand
filter projects.

281
00:19:12,940 --> 00:19:15,610
Clear Cambodia had distributed more than
60,000

282
00:19:15,610 --> 00:19:19,700
Biosand filters in rural Cambodia, by
2010.

283
00:19:19,700 --> 00:19:22,610
They received additional funding from
Samaritan's

284
00:19:22,610 --> 00:19:27,870
Purse to implement another 15,600 new
filters.

285
00:19:27,870 --> 00:19:32,750
So they created demand through social
mobilization visits to

286
00:19:32,750 --> 00:19:37,420
schools and villages, with demonstrations
of the Biosand filter technology.

287
00:19:37,420 --> 00:19:42,390
And they trained community health
promoters to solicit requests for

288
00:19:42,390 --> 00:19:47,546
filters and were tremendously successful,
generating

289
00:19:47,546 --> 00:19:52,920
150,000 requests, almost ten times as much
demand as their supply plan.

290
00:19:54,850 --> 00:19:57,180
Clear Cambodia then traveled from village
to

291
00:19:57,180 --> 00:20:01,430
village and built concrete Biosand filters
on site.

292
00:20:01,430 --> 00:20:06,290
And then after implementation filters were
monitored repeatedly

293
00:20:06,290 --> 00:20:08,800
with four visits in the year after
installation.

294
00:20:10,900 --> 00:20:12,830
The full cost of one Biosand filter in

295
00:20:12,830 --> 00:20:16,380
this project is about $60, including all
of the

296
00:20:16,380 --> 00:20:20,490
costs associated with distribution and
monitoring, and this price

297
00:20:20,490 --> 00:20:23,140
is well out of reach of their target
population.

298
00:20:24,140 --> 00:20:26,940
Clear Cambodia does sell filters at full
price to other

299
00:20:26,940 --> 00:20:31,180
NGOs and government, but filters for the
poor are heavily subsidized.

300
00:20:32,390 --> 00:20:35,290
Clear Cambodia does ask for user
contributions

301
00:20:35,290 --> 00:20:38,192
including a nominal cash contribution of
about

302
00:20:38,192 --> 00:20:45,510
$4 US, as well as in-kind contributions of
time and materials such as sand.

303
00:20:45,510 --> 00:20:48,550
Also people have to arrange their own
transport to the

304
00:20:48,550 --> 00:20:51,430
household level which is not trivial,
these are heavy things.

305
00:20:53,040 --> 00:20:57,571
And they must also commit to joining
promotion meetings and follow-up visits.

306
00:20:57,571 --> 00:21:03,160
Unlike the profit-maximizing approaches of
other filters, the main cost

307
00:21:03,160 --> 00:21:07,450
of a Biosand filter is the initial
construction and distribution.

308
00:21:07,450 --> 00:21:10,340
There are no recurring expenses, and
operation

309
00:21:10,340 --> 00:21:13,310
and maintenance are relatively easy and
free.

310
00:21:15,640 --> 00:21:20,370
One of the biggest barriers to getting
HWTS technologies in the hands of BOP

311
00:21:20,370 --> 00:21:25,840
consumers is the high capital costs,
especially for durable goods like filters.

312
00:21:27,150 --> 00:21:32,000
Both for-profit companies and social
businesses are actively experimenting with

313
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:36,060
innovations in financing that could allow
this barrier to be reduced.

314
00:21:37,340 --> 00:21:39,860
A few companies, including Unilever, have

315
00:21:39,860 --> 00:21:43,950
tried micro-credit, with initial promising
results.

316
00:21:43,950 --> 00:21:49,010
Others have looked at payments and
installments or group saving approaches.

317
00:21:49,010 --> 00:21:52,190
And there's a lot of interest in mobile
payments, especially in

318
00:21:52,190 --> 00:21:54,670
East Africa where the mobile payment

319
00:21:54,670 --> 00:21:57,590
programs MPesa, has seen tremendous
success.

320
00:21:59,080 --> 00:22:02,165
And finally, one original approach is to
attempt to

321
00:22:02,165 --> 00:22:06,750
cross-subsidize the cost of HWTS through
carbon credit revenues.

322
00:22:08,010 --> 00:22:11,570
The idea here is that a household
practicing HWTS doesn't

323
00:22:11,570 --> 00:22:14,690
